The other big question is inference =E2=80=94 the actual leveraging of trai=
ned models =E2=80=94 which is going to be a much larger market than trainin=
g: there is a gargantuan amount of motivation to drive inference capabiliti=
es down to local hardware, and barring that, to make it as cost-effective i=
n the server as possible. Nvidia still has the best capabilities here, but =
the interconnect and networking capabilities necessary are much lower than =
for training, which makes it more likely that AMD in particular can build a=
 competitive product.

That noted, Nvidia is very fortunate that that the generative AI moment hap=
pened now, when its chips are clearly superior: the deepest moats that Huan=
g presented are all about software and developers, and right now the number=
 of CUDA developers and applications built on Nvidia frameworks are explodi=
ng. Sure, you can definitely argue that we are in a bubble =E2=80=94 AI cap=
abilities are obviously incredible, but it will take time to actually creat=
e useful products =E2=80=94 but there are real skills and models and framew=
orks being developed now that, I suspect, are more differentiated than Sola=
ris, the operating system for Sun Microsystems, was from Linux.

That=E2=80=99s the key point: long-term differentiation in tech is always r=
ooted in software and ecosystems, even if long-term value-capture has often=
 been rooted in hardware; what makes Nvidia so compelling is that they, lik=
e Apple, combine both.

